=== READING TALLY MARKS ===

Surveyors record fish counts using TALLY MARKS (stroke notation):
  I = 1, II = 2, III = 3, IIII = 4, IIII with a diagonal strike = 5 (a "gate")
  Example: IIII IIII II = 12 (two gates + two strokes)

CRITICAL rules for reading tallies:
- Tally groups of 5 have a diagonal line crossing four vertical strokes
- Count each group of 5 carefully, then add remaining strokes
- Distinguish between tally marks and stray marks/smudges from the pen
- A single vertical stroke "I" in a cell = count of 1, not a stray mark
- Two single vertical strokes "II" in a cell = count of 2, not eleven
- If marks span across column gridlines, assign them to the column where
  the BASE of the strokes sits
- Faint or light marks still count — surveyors sometimes write lightly
  underwater or in difficult conditions

=== TRANSECT HANDLING ===

The "Transect" field in the header indicates which transect number(s) this
sheet covers. The filename may also indicate the transect (e.g., "_T1" = Transect 1).

Some sheets cover multiple transects on one page. When this happens:
- The surveyor draws a horizontal line across the tally columns at some point
  to mark the boundary between transects
- Tallies ABOVE the line belong to the first transect
- Tallies BELOW the line belong to the next transect
- If you see this, output separate data blocks for each transect

For single-transect sheets, output one transect block.

=== HANDLING ANNOTATIONS ===

Surveyors sometimes write notes in margins or on the sheet:
- "① right" or similar = page ordering notes (ignore for data extraction)
- Circled numbers = typically page sequence
- Arrows or brackets = grouping indicators
- "Checked/Entered/Scanned" boxes at top = processing status (note but don't extract)

